\chapter{Introduction}


Systemic effects are system-wide effects which are triggered through local interaction. That means, systemic effects in a system can not be boiled down to a simple aggregates of properties of its units but only through more complex ones. Thus, the understanding of systemic effects in socio-economic systems is crucial for good anticipation of potential societal change and the proper design of societal institutions. 
Entanglement and understanding of the relation of microscopic rules of action and interaction to macroscopic effects is the core contributions of this habilitation. 

Studying potential systemic effects scientifically requires a well-suited description the units of a system and their action and interaction. For socio-economic systems that means the developement of an agent-based model with humans (or firms and organisations) as the agents. Agents' actions and interactions are defined based on behavioral rules which might be derived from utility functions which agents want to maximize or satisfice. 

\textbf{Agent-based models} can be studied with computer simulations. How this generally works and how it is used to tackle political science research questions is the subject of one part of the habilitation work:

