\chapter{Opinion Dynamics}

When individuals form opinions on certain topics these are based on the one hand on individual knowledge, experience, and emotions, but on the other hand opinions are to a large extent intrinsically social. We adjust our existing opinions once we hear the opinions of others because we learn new information, or because we want to conform with or confront the opinions of others. Sometimes we consciously might form our opinions entirely based on how it best fits in the opinion landscapes of our social environment. 

How individuals adjust their opinions with respect to messages from other is has been studied in \emph{social psychology} for a long time in the field of \emph{attitude research}. The focus of the \emph{opinion dynamics} goes beyond the individual and studies the effect which the repeated simultaneous opinion formation and opinion adjustments transforms and shapes the entire opinion landscape. Thus, opinion dynamics extends the view from individual processes to systemic processes triggered by them. 

