\chapter{The Wisdom of Crowds}

 The wisdom of the crowd phenomenon is when the aggregate of several individual estimates is close to the true value although most estimates are far away from it. 
 
 The seminal example is the weight-judging competition at the West England Fat Stock and Poultry Exhibition for which \textcite{Galton1907Voxpopuli} collected 787 card on which competitors estimated the weight of the meat of an ox (after it has been slaughtered and dressed). The 5\%-percentile and the 95\%-percentile spannded values from 1,074 to 1,293 pounds, while the median (middlemost) value was 1,207 which was surprisingly close to the correct value of 1,198 pounds. Galton concludes: \textit{``This result is, I think more credible to the trustworthiness of a democratic judgment than might have been expected.''} 
 
 An even more drastic example is a follow up of this 
 
 Which aggregate (e.g. arithmetic mean, the geometric mean, the median, or the mode) is used is sometimes crucial for the existence of the phenomenon. 
 
 The wisdom of the crowd effect appears surprising to most individuals although it is a natural statistical property when we see individual estimates as independent random draws a distribution which is unbiased in the sense that the aggregate measure coincides with the correct value. 


